  "text": "Note that the converse to Lemma 3 is true if r[(l(T ) \\ Rb] = rl(T ) + r(b) holds for all right ideals T of R and all b 2 R: In fact, if l(T ) \\ Rb = 0 this gives rl(T ) + r(b) = R so lr(b) = 0 by hypothesis. Hence b = 0 because Rb lr(b); proving that l(T ) ess R R: In particular, the converse holds if R is a right Ikeda-Nakayama ring [CITATION_1] , that is r[L \\ K] = r(L) + r(K) for any left ideals L and K:",
